WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.238 --> 00:00:08.029
DOUG LIPP: Welcome.

00:00:08.029 --> 00:00:09.290
Thank you for being here today.

00:00:09.290 --> 00:00:11.331
And I would like to share
with you some thoughts.

00:00:11.331 --> 00:00:15.180
And [? Marjay ?] talked a
little bit about my background--

00:00:15.180 --> 00:00:19.250
a bit more is I
work for Disneyland.

00:00:19.250 --> 00:00:21.790
My first job at Disney,
outside of being an intern,

00:00:21.790 --> 00:00:23.125
was as a Japanese interpreter.

00:00:24.210 --> 00:00:26.080
My second language
is Japanese, and I

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:28.850
was doing some work
for the newly hired,

00:00:28.850 --> 00:00:31.102
newly brought on
board executives

00:00:31.102 --> 00:00:32.810
from Japan that were
going to be starting

00:00:32.810 --> 00:00:35.200
our first international
theme park.

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:37.700
So while I was a college
student working at Disneyland,

00:00:37.700 --> 00:00:38.880
I was studying Japanese.

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:40.230
And I knew that they
were going to go

00:00:40.230 --> 00:00:41.480
into the international market.

00:00:41.480 --> 00:00:43.320
But I wasn't sure
when and where.

00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:44.940
And when I was in
grad school in Tokyo

00:00:44.940 --> 00:00:48.620
I got a message from a colleague
who said they decided on Tokyo.

00:00:48.620 --> 00:00:50.660
So I knew I had to come back.

00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:52.786
And the first thing out
of the executive's mouth,

00:00:52.786 --> 00:00:54.410
he said, well, you
know, Disney's style

00:00:54.410 --> 00:00:55.500
is you've got to
start at the bottom.

00:00:55.500 --> 00:00:57.890
So you can either start as
a ride operator, a street

00:00:57.890 --> 00:00:59.145
sweeper, or an interpreter.

00:00:59.145 --> 00:01:00.630
And I said I'll
be an interpreter.

00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:02.000
That's what I'm doing.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.180
And I got exposed to the men and
women who ran the university.

00:01:06.180 --> 00:01:07.920
I got to work with a
lot of great people

00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:09.310
and start a whole new project.

00:01:09.310 --> 00:01:11.309
And you know what it's
like to start new things.

00:01:11.309 --> 00:01:12.450
You wear lots of hats.

00:01:12.450 --> 00:01:14.860
So I went from Disneyland
and then I went to Japan.

00:01:14.860 --> 00:01:17.580
I was transferred back to
Japan for several years.

00:01:17.580 --> 00:01:20.510
So I got to live in Japan
as a starving student and as

00:01:20.510 --> 00:01:22.270
a ridiculously overpaid expat.

00:01:22.270 --> 00:01:24.745
And it's a lot better to be
a ridiculously paid expat.

00:01:24.745 --> 00:01:26.870
And I spent several years
there getting the park up

00:01:26.870 --> 00:01:27.370
and running.

00:01:27.370 --> 00:01:29.797
And I'll share with you a
couple of stories from that.

00:01:29.797 --> 00:01:32.130
And then I came back, and I
went to Disney headquarters,

00:01:32.130 --> 00:01:34.500
which is their studios.

00:01:34.500 --> 00:01:38.110
And the whole time I was
in the Disney organization,

00:01:38.110 --> 00:01:40.610
I was exposed to
men and women who

00:01:40.610 --> 00:01:42.210
worked directly
with Walt Disney.

00:01:43.340 --> 00:01:46.110
Now, you probably don't
realize how blessed

00:01:46.110 --> 00:01:48.880
you are to be in
such a young company.

00:01:48.880 --> 00:01:52.230
What are you celebrating--
Sweet 16 this year, right?

00:01:52.230 --> 00:01:57.490
And you have contact with
Larry, with Sergey, with Eric.

00:01:57.490 --> 00:01:59.190
I never got to meet Walt Disney.

00:01:59.190 --> 00:02:02.750
Walt Disney passed away
in 1966, and in those days

00:02:02.750 --> 00:02:04.850
they were not hiring
11-year-olds to run

00:02:04.850 --> 00:02:05.940
the company.

00:02:05.940 --> 00:02:08.259
But the men and women
that mentored me did

00:02:08.259 --> 00:02:09.679
get to work with Walt.

00:02:09.679 --> 00:02:11.970
So I'm going to share with
you some thoughts about that

00:02:11.970 --> 00:02:12.650
as we go along.

00:02:12.650 --> 00:02:14.040
Is the slide-- woohoo!

00:02:15.470 --> 00:02:17.814
That's why your heads are
going like this right now.

00:02:17.814 --> 00:02:19.230
As that gets set
up and running, I

00:02:19.230 --> 00:02:21.290
want to share with you
something else just

00:02:21.290 --> 00:02:24.550
to set the tone for what
an amazingly qualified guy

00:02:24.550 --> 00:02:26.220
I am to be speaking
to you today.

00:02:27.850 --> 00:02:29.970
You know, you at Google
are so cocky about how

00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:32.240
cool your culture is
and how fun it is.

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:34.155
You got nothing on Disney.

00:02:35.410 --> 00:02:40.040
When I worked at the studios,
I participated in a voice

00:02:40.040 --> 00:02:45.000
contest-- a voice contest-- we
lovingly called it a quack-off.

00:02:47.012 --> 00:02:47.720
Think about that.

00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:49.060
You can't say that
word in Missouri,

00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:50.480
but you could say in California.

00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:52.470
I participated in
a voice contest

00:02:52.470 --> 00:02:54.895
to celebrate Donald
Duck's birthday.

00:02:55.980 --> 00:02:59.800
This was put on by what's
called the Mickey Mouse Activity

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:03.330
Center, which is the activity
center for all the employees.

00:03:03.330 --> 00:03:05.430
You have all the
recreation, canoe races,

00:03:05.430 --> 00:03:06.880
all kinds of stuff, right?

00:03:06.880 --> 00:03:09.180
It makes Googleplex look
like a boring library.

00:03:10.380 --> 00:03:14.350
And I participated in this
only because the woman who

00:03:14.350 --> 00:03:17.570
was in charge of putting it
on had kind of caught my eye.

00:03:17.570 --> 00:03:20.124
I thought she was kind of cool
looking, and she kept saying,

00:03:20.124 --> 00:03:22.040
would you please participate
in the quack-off?

00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:23.029
We need more quackers.

00:03:23.029 --> 00:03:24.445
We need to have
more participants.

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:27.990
And I thought, well,
maybe if I participate,

00:03:27.990 --> 00:03:29.400
you'll go on a date with me.

00:03:30.450 --> 00:03:33.340
So I did, and I won
the competition.

00:03:34.697 --> 00:03:36.280
And I won the girl,
and she's actually

00:03:36.280 --> 00:03:37.210
in the back of the
room right there

00:03:37.210 --> 00:03:38.729
in that beautiful blue dress.

00:03:38.729 --> 00:03:39.520
Hello, [INAUDIBLE]!

00:03:42.860 --> 00:03:45.220
Actually, it was kind of
a surreal environment.

00:03:45.220 --> 00:03:47.820
The man who was the
emcee of the activity

00:03:47.820 --> 00:03:49.561
was the voice of Mickey Mouse.

00:03:49.561 --> 00:03:52.060
Well, at the time, the guy who
was the voice of Mickey Mouse

00:03:52.060 --> 00:03:53.970
was about 6' 3",
had a full beard.

00:03:53.970 --> 00:03:56.220
He looked like a lumberjack,
[MICKEY MOUSE IMPRESSION]

00:03:56.220 --> 00:03:57.920
but he talked like this.

00:03:57.920 --> 00:04:00.810
So it was really surreal to
look up at this giant guy

00:04:00.810 --> 00:04:02.660
and think, oh my
gosh, that's Mickey.

00:04:02.660 --> 00:04:06.340
And the man who had been the
voice of Donald for years

00:04:06.340 --> 00:04:07.260
was going to retire.

00:04:07.260 --> 00:04:08.400
He was in his mid '80s.

00:04:09.460 --> 00:04:12.320
His name was
Clarence Ducky Nash.

00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:15.871
And so we participated in
this quack-off and I won.

00:04:15.871 --> 00:04:17.620
(DONALD DUCK IMPRESSION)
Hello, everybody.

00:04:17.620 --> 00:04:18.845
How are you today?

00:04:18.845 --> 00:04:20.266
Ah-- ah-- ah-choo.

00:04:22.198 --> 00:04:25.096
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:28.490 --> 00:04:30.760
And the guy who came
in second is now

00:04:30.760 --> 00:04:31.950
the voice of Donald Duck.

00:04:31.950 --> 00:04:32.500
Go figure.

00:04:34.147 --> 00:04:36.355
But anyway, I really want
to think about-- this is up

00:04:36.355 --> 00:04:38.938
and running now? [? Marjay, ?]
thank you-- leadership, service

00:04:38.938 --> 00:04:39.630
magic.

00:04:39.630 --> 00:04:42.670
I'm going to share with you
some thoughts today about both

00:04:42.670 --> 00:04:44.740
my career Disney,
but more importantly,

00:04:44.740 --> 00:04:47.150
some of the lessons
that I learned,

00:04:47.150 --> 00:04:49.980
and they are in this
bestselling book.

00:04:49.980 --> 00:04:51.490
You can use it as a door stop.

00:04:51.490 --> 00:04:52.990
You can use it as a sleep aid.

00:04:52.990 --> 00:04:53.810
It's really cool.

00:04:53.810 --> 00:04:55.662
No, actually,
based on subsidies,

00:04:55.662 --> 00:04:57.120
you guys have a
pretty good dealer.

00:04:57.120 --> 00:04:58.980
And I just want to let
you know, for those of you

00:04:58.980 --> 00:05:00.470
that buy this book,
we are donating

00:05:00.470 --> 00:05:03.580
all proceeds to an organization
called NAMI-- National

00:05:03.580 --> 00:05:06.000
Alliance on Mental
Illness-- to help reduce

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:07.540
the stigma associated with that.

00:05:07.540 --> 00:05:09.140
But in here I have quotes.

00:05:09.140 --> 00:05:11.430
I have ideas from
many men and women,

00:05:11.430 --> 00:05:13.770
but in particular,
the man who I referred

00:05:13.770 --> 00:05:17.560
to earlier as the
mentor that helped me

00:05:17.560 --> 00:05:20.720
for many, many years--
a guy named Van France.

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:26.040
Van France was hired directly
by Walt Disney in early 1955.

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:28.770
Disneyland opened
in July of '55.

00:05:28.770 --> 00:05:31.630
And Walt was smart
enough to realize

00:05:31.630 --> 00:05:34.990
that he and his team of
designers, architects,

00:05:34.990 --> 00:05:37.760
construction people,
ride engineers,

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:41.250
were architects of
things, of science.

00:05:41.250 --> 00:05:44.390
And they needed a person to
be the architect of people

00:05:44.390 --> 00:05:45.240
development.

00:05:45.240 --> 00:05:47.400
Much like you have a
chief cultural officer--

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:50.010
HR director-- Van
France would've

00:05:50.010 --> 00:05:52.340
been the chief cultural
officer of the day.

00:05:53.890 --> 00:05:56.026
And he's the one who started
the Disney University.

00:05:56.026 --> 00:05:57.900
It wasn't known as the
University originally,

00:05:57.900 --> 00:06:00.300
but he's the man who
created the university.

00:06:00.300 --> 00:06:04.340
So I want to share with you some
thoughts about what Van brought

00:06:04.340 --> 00:06:07.140
to the table and compare
and contrast, seriously,

00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:09.310
the amazing culture
that you belong to.

00:06:09.310 --> 00:06:13.110
You think about Googlers and
Nooglers and Googleplex and all

00:06:13.110 --> 00:06:15.850
of the vernacular that
this young company

00:06:15.850 --> 00:06:19.054
has created in such a
short amount of time.

00:06:19.054 --> 00:06:20.970
You have to have a
tremendous amount of pride.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:23.850
I feel the same
way about Disney.

00:06:23.850 --> 00:06:26.590
We had our own vernacular
which has lived--

00:06:26.590 --> 00:06:31.000
Disneyland is going on 60
years of age now-- cast member,

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:34.895
on-stage, backstage,
good show, bad show.

00:06:34.895 --> 00:06:35.770
But here's the point.

00:06:36.920 --> 00:06:39.420
The culture is a lot
more than just words.

00:06:39.420 --> 00:06:42.070
It's a lot more than
fanciful colored bikes.

00:06:42.070 --> 00:06:44.220
It's a lot more
than free lunches.

00:06:44.220 --> 00:06:45.930
It's a lot of hard work.

00:06:45.930 --> 00:06:48.240
And I'll share with
you briefly how

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:50.660
we squandered that at Disney.

00:06:50.660 --> 00:06:53.390
We actually almost
lost the entire company

00:06:53.390 --> 00:06:57.100
not once, but twice,
in a 20-year period,

00:06:57.100 --> 00:07:00.080
despite the name recognition,
the international brand,

00:07:00.080 --> 00:07:03.420
and love for all the characters
and all the attractions we'd

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:05.740
built, and movies and songs
and that sort of thing.

00:07:05.740 --> 00:07:09.730
So yes, enjoy your
unique culture

00:07:09.730 --> 00:07:11.900
and your position in
the world and constantly

00:07:11.900 --> 00:07:14.100
being put on a
pedestal and recognized

00:07:14.100 --> 00:07:17.360
as one of the best employers
in the world and to have such

00:07:17.360 --> 00:07:19.910
a great environment
in which to work.

00:07:19.910 --> 00:07:20.710
I envy you.

00:07:21.870 --> 00:07:23.430
Enjoy it while you
have it right now.

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:24.830
Enjoy it in your youth.

00:07:24.830 --> 00:07:27.250
Enjoy it as you
get older, as well.

00:07:27.250 --> 00:07:30.140
So I'm going to share with
you a thought from Van

00:07:30.140 --> 00:07:33.770
France in this slide I've
got right now-- capturing

00:07:33.770 --> 00:07:37.960
hearts and minds fosters
trust and innovation.

00:07:37.960 --> 00:07:39.870
Again, Walt Disney
was smart enough

00:07:39.870 --> 00:07:43.339
to realize that his team and he
had to focus on the hardware,

00:07:43.339 --> 00:07:44.880
on the rides, and
on the attractions.

00:07:46.310 --> 00:07:48.690
But who was going to
get those cast members

00:07:48.690 --> 00:07:50.990
on board that were
going to create

00:07:50.990 --> 00:07:52.830
the happiest place on earth?

00:07:52.830 --> 00:07:55.450
People that didn't know a
thing about theme parks,

00:07:55.450 --> 00:07:57.620
because theme parks had
not yet been invented.

00:07:58.790 --> 00:08:02.160
16-year-olds to 85-year-olds,
and everything in between--

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:03.650
how do we do that?

00:08:03.650 --> 00:08:05.800
And so Van created
this environment.

00:08:05.800 --> 00:08:09.510
And he learned that that
environment existed for decades

00:08:09.510 --> 00:08:12.230
before he ever saw Disneyland.

00:08:12.230 --> 00:08:14.980
Let me read one little
excerpt from the book

00:08:14.980 --> 00:08:19.960
that I use to kind of set
the tone for what Van walked

00:08:19.960 --> 00:08:24.120
into when he realized that
his own quirky sense of humor

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:26.510
was going to fit in
perfectly with Walt Disney's

00:08:26.510 --> 00:08:27.770
quirky sense of humor.

00:08:29.110 --> 00:08:33.200
So I say in here, "Van
first met Walt in 1954.

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:35.289
Then he was asked
to join the company.

00:08:36.299 --> 00:08:38.623
He said, I was asked
to meet Walt Disney.

00:08:38.623 --> 00:08:40.789
And the meeting was held
in the animation building."

00:08:40.789 --> 00:08:43.767
This is where all the artists
reside at the Disney Studios

00:08:43.767 --> 00:08:44.725
in Burbank, California.

00:08:46.011 --> 00:08:48.010
"The meeting was held in
the animation building,

00:08:48.010 --> 00:08:49.200
home to all the artists.

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:52.030
And it's also were Walt's
office was located.

00:08:52.030 --> 00:08:56.020
I parked in the visitor's
lot and set off on foot

00:08:56.020 --> 00:09:00.230
down Snow White Lane,
past Dopey Drive,

00:09:00.230 --> 00:09:04.140
until I came to Mickey Mouse
Avenue and the studio's

00:09:04.140 --> 00:09:06.630
three-story animation building."

00:09:06.630 --> 00:09:09.670
This is from a man who worked
in World War II factories.

00:09:09.670 --> 00:09:11.970
He worked in aluminum
smelting plants.

00:09:11.970 --> 00:09:14.380
He worked in anything
but a fun environment,

00:09:14.380 --> 00:09:17.260
but he was an irascible
character himself.

00:09:17.260 --> 00:09:19.320
In fact, one of the
ways the we described

00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:21.272
Van France to our
fellow colleagues

00:09:21.272 --> 00:09:22.730
who never got a
chance to meet him,

00:09:22.730 --> 00:09:26.600
was he was a combination of
a Snow White-kind of person,

00:09:26.600 --> 00:09:29.060
but really he was more
like Mary Poppins.

00:09:29.060 --> 00:09:32.410
He was beautiful
in soul and spirit.

00:09:32.410 --> 00:09:35.480
And he was a guiding
light like Mary Poppins.

00:09:35.480 --> 00:09:38.680
He was like Jiminy
Cricket guiding Pinocchio

00:09:38.680 --> 00:09:39.790
down the right path.

00:09:39.790 --> 00:09:44.760
So we kept us on track to keep
Walt Disney's dream alive.

00:09:44.760 --> 00:09:46.950
But he was also like
an angry Donald Duck.

00:09:46.950 --> 00:09:48.770
And Donald's known to
have a short temper.

00:09:48.770 --> 00:09:52.320
And if you gave excuses,
he would get in your grill

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:54.750
immediately and let you know
in no uncertain terms what

00:09:54.750 --> 00:09:56.840
was wrong and how
you had to fix it.

00:09:56.840 --> 00:09:59.290
In fact, one of Walt's
favorite quotes-- and Van

00:09:59.290 --> 00:10:03.485
taught this to me-- was "don't
come to me with no, because.

00:10:04.620 --> 00:10:07.570
Come to me with yes, if."

00:10:07.570 --> 00:10:09.240
And that opened up
all kinds of doors

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:10.615
of creativity and opportunity.

00:10:12.310 --> 00:10:14.780
So this thing about capturing
hearts and minds-- and one

00:10:14.780 --> 00:10:17.865
of the things we tried
to do-- and I think

00:10:17.865 --> 00:10:19.740
did it pretty well in
the Disney University--

00:10:19.740 --> 00:10:23.490
when we would have new
hire orientation every week

00:10:23.490 --> 00:10:25.830
before a busy season at
Disneyland or Walt Disney

00:10:25.830 --> 00:10:26.610
World.

00:10:26.610 --> 00:10:29.370
We'd have 60 to 80
to 90 new hires.

00:10:29.370 --> 00:10:31.100
We didn't call then
Nooglers like you do,

00:10:31.100 --> 00:10:34.050
but they were just called
new hires-- new cast members.

00:10:34.050 --> 00:10:36.330
And we had eight hours
to inculcate them,

00:10:36.330 --> 00:10:38.020
to get them excited.

00:10:38.020 --> 00:10:40.360
And in addition a sprinkling
a lot of pixie dust

00:10:40.360 --> 00:10:42.193
on their heads, we did
a lot of other things

00:10:42.193 --> 00:10:43.861
to capture their
hearts and minds.

00:10:43.861 --> 00:10:45.860
And one of the most
important things that we did

00:10:45.860 --> 00:10:49.400
was this-- we talked about
the importance of teamwork,

00:10:49.400 --> 00:10:52.050
of cleanliness, and friendliness
that our customers paid

00:10:52.050 --> 00:10:53.940
a premium for.

00:10:53.940 --> 00:10:56.570
They'd pay a premium to come
to Disney, because it's clean.

00:10:56.570 --> 00:10:58.940
It's safe, and the rides work.

00:10:58.940 --> 00:11:02.140
Yes, Universal Studios might
have faster, sexier rides,

00:11:02.140 --> 00:11:03.550
but they break
down all the time.

00:11:03.550 --> 00:11:06.030
And they might have more
employees, but they're snarky.

00:11:06.030 --> 00:11:08.517
If you ask a Universal
employee, where's the washroom,

00:11:08.517 --> 00:11:10.100
they're going to
say, it's over there.

00:11:10.100 --> 00:11:11.374
Can't you smell it?

00:11:13.150 --> 00:11:14.600
But if you ask a
Disney employee,

00:11:14.600 --> 00:11:15.220
they're going to stop.

00:11:15.220 --> 00:11:17.303
They're going to look at
you, and say, sir, ma'am,

00:11:17.303 --> 00:11:19.720
it's right this way,
with an open palm.

00:11:19.720 --> 00:11:21.250
But we would talk about this.

00:11:21.250 --> 00:11:22.800
We would show videos.

00:11:22.800 --> 00:11:24.600
But it's still at
the cognitive level.

00:11:24.600 --> 00:11:26.050
It's just at the brain level.

00:11:26.050 --> 00:11:28.110
How do we capture their hearts?

00:11:28.110 --> 00:11:30.620
And so the last
hour of orientation,

00:11:30.620 --> 00:11:32.355
we would take them
through the park.

00:11:33.929 --> 00:11:35.470
We would talk about
the architecture.

00:11:35.470 --> 00:11:38.600
We would talk about the
theming, but our primary goal

00:11:38.600 --> 00:11:41.430
was for them to see
with their own eyes

00:11:41.430 --> 00:11:45.090
multiple examples of
non-custodial personnel bending

00:11:45.090 --> 00:11:47.580
over and picking up
trash, executives going

00:11:47.580 --> 00:11:51.350
to and from staff meetings,
cast members-- obviously

00:11:51.350 --> 00:11:54.270
not custodians-- going
to or from breaks,

00:11:54.270 --> 00:11:55.810
bending over and
picking up trash,

00:11:55.810 --> 00:11:58.060
and as soon as my
new hires saw that, I

00:11:58.060 --> 00:11:59.730
know that I've
captured their hearts.

00:11:59.730 --> 00:12:01.515
Now they're thinking,
oh, yes, what

00:12:01.515 --> 00:12:03.890
they talked about there in
the Never Never Land of Disney

00:12:03.890 --> 00:12:06.070
University actually happens.

00:12:06.070 --> 00:12:08.905
Where, all too often
I see organizations--

00:12:08.905 --> 00:12:11.660
and I'm not saying Google--
but a lot of organizations

00:12:11.660 --> 00:12:14.630
try to emulate the Google
culture, the Disney

00:12:14.630 --> 00:12:17.540
culture, and metaphorically--
like I have on the slide here--

00:12:17.540 --> 00:12:22.261
try to put up a coat of paint
on a dilapidated, run-down

00:12:22.261 --> 00:12:22.760
building.

00:12:22.760 --> 00:12:25.640
The culture isn't strong,
or it's not even set up yet.

00:12:25.640 --> 00:12:28.150
But they think just by
having fanciful names,

00:12:28.150 --> 00:12:30.130
colorful t-shirts, or
really cool posters

00:12:30.130 --> 00:12:32.450
on the wall, that'll
make people buy in.

00:12:32.450 --> 00:12:34.750
Ultimately those posters
become the butt of jokes

00:12:34.750 --> 00:12:38.010
if people aren't living
and breathing that culture.

00:12:38.010 --> 00:12:40.672
To this day, I can't
walk across the property,

00:12:40.672 --> 00:12:42.130
see a piece of
trash on the ground,

00:12:42.130 --> 00:12:45.960
and not go into the automatic
robot rote of must bend over

00:12:45.960 --> 00:12:46.885
and pick up trash.

00:12:48.350 --> 00:12:53.170
So kudos to you, for in
a short amount of time,

00:12:53.170 --> 00:12:55.950
creating such a strong
culture, because culture

00:12:55.950 --> 00:12:59.380
happens in one of two
ways-- either by design,

00:12:59.380 --> 00:13:01.180
or by benign neglect.

00:13:01.180 --> 00:13:03.340
And all too often I
see benign neglect

00:13:03.340 --> 00:13:06.602
taking the stage, people not
really trying to mold it,

00:13:06.602 --> 00:13:07.560
just letting it happen.

