AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:13:37.120 --> 00:13:38.790
I'd love to hear
more about how you

00:13:38.790 --> 00:13:43.120
got beyond the cognitive
level of helping people absorb

00:13:43.120 --> 00:13:45.980
that culture and even
the reinforcement.

00:13:45.980 --> 00:13:49.880
DOUG LIPP: Getting beyond the
cognitive level is really--

00:13:49.880 --> 00:13:52.640
what was being said in the
classroom in the Disney

00:13:52.640 --> 00:13:57.300
University was happening
every day on the job.

00:13:57.300 --> 00:14:00.070
And so it didn't remove it
from the cognitive level.

00:14:00.070 --> 00:14:04.290
It just blended the cognitive
and the gut level into one.

00:14:04.290 --> 00:14:07.000
There was congruence
between the message,

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:09.170
because in the
University, we had

00:14:09.170 --> 00:14:11.630
people who had
operations background.

00:14:11.630 --> 00:14:13.410
Operations people
always filtered

00:14:13.410 --> 00:14:14.870
through the University.

00:14:14.870 --> 00:14:17.870
So when you walked out as
a newly hired employee,

00:14:17.870 --> 00:14:21.040
or as a mid-level manager,
or when Michael Eisner

00:14:21.040 --> 00:14:24.090
joined the company-- and I had
him in the Disney University.

00:14:24.090 --> 00:14:25.670
In fact on the
back of that book,

00:14:25.670 --> 00:14:28.190
you'll see Michael wrote
a testimonial saying, when

00:14:28.190 --> 00:14:31.580
I joined Disney as the CEO,
I had to go back to school,

00:14:31.580 --> 00:14:35.200
to the University-- when the
CEO walks into the University

00:14:35.200 --> 00:14:37.320
as the equivalent
of a Noogler, that

00:14:37.320 --> 00:14:39.940
sends a massively powerful
message to everybody

00:14:39.940 --> 00:14:41.290
else in the organization.

00:14:41.290 --> 00:14:44.590
When I was in charge of training
at Disney Studios, that's

00:14:44.590 --> 00:14:47.540
a whole different ball
game, training 35-

00:14:47.540 --> 00:14:49.980
to 85-year-old
Hollywood executives--

00:14:49.980 --> 00:14:52.990
they're a tough crowd-- versus
the bright-eyed, bushy-tailed

00:14:52.990 --> 00:14:54.990
kids you get at Disney
World or Disneyland.

00:14:54.990 --> 00:14:56.880
I wasn't going to fight
the battle of having

00:14:56.880 --> 00:14:58.830
a discussion about
creativity with them.

00:14:58.830 --> 00:15:03.340
I would call in the chairman of
Disney Studios, Dick Cook, who

00:15:03.340 --> 00:15:06.550
was in charge of running
a huge corporation.

00:15:06.550 --> 00:15:08.590
He's the man who
brought in Johnny Depp

00:15:08.590 --> 00:15:10.844
to do all the "Pirates" series.

00:15:10.844 --> 00:15:12.260
When he walked in
a room and said,

00:15:12.260 --> 00:15:14.230
hey, let's have a
discussion for 30 minutes

00:15:14.230 --> 00:15:16.850
about the creative process
of creating a film,

00:15:16.850 --> 00:15:18.810
you capture people's
hearts and minds.

00:15:18.810 --> 00:15:20.660
And that was the
message is that, if it's

00:15:20.660 --> 00:15:22.830
good enough for a
16-year-old new hire,

00:15:22.830 --> 00:15:24.720
it's good enough for
that senior executive

00:15:24.720 --> 00:15:25.800
and everybody in between.

00:15:25.800 --> 00:15:27.740
So that became part
of the culture.

00:15:27.740 --> 00:15:29.650
And when it becomes
part of the culture,

00:15:29.650 --> 00:15:31.450
you take it out of
the cognitive realm

00:15:31.450 --> 00:15:32.890
and you put it
right in the heart.

00:15:32.890 --> 00:15:34.150
All right, so let's push on.

00:15:34.150 --> 00:15:37.080
Again, in short, the
Disney University

00:15:37.080 --> 00:15:39.630
is not a standalone
fix-it operation.

00:15:39.630 --> 00:15:42.550
It's a vehicle for the
culture of the organization.

00:15:42.550 --> 00:15:45.172
It's part and parcel to what
the company's all about.

00:15:45.172 --> 00:15:46.630
So what I'm showing
you right now--

00:15:46.630 --> 00:15:48.190
and it really does feed
in nicely, in fact.

00:15:48.190 --> 00:15:49.106
Thank you for the cue.

00:15:49.106 --> 00:15:51.240
You'll get your bonus
after the presentation's

00:15:51.240 --> 00:15:55.130
over-- Van France,
again, my mentor, talked

00:15:55.130 --> 00:15:58.490
about why does the
University survive?

00:15:58.490 --> 00:16:01.030
And I have to tell you as a
training and development OD

00:16:01.030 --> 00:16:02.950
specialist-- I
consult with companies

00:16:02.950 --> 00:16:05.050
all around the
world-- all too often

00:16:05.050 --> 00:16:08.010
I have people who will challenge
me and say, well, of course,

00:16:08.010 --> 00:16:10.240
the Disney University
has success.

00:16:10.240 --> 00:16:12.080
I mean, if I had
Mickey Mouse leading

00:16:12.080 --> 00:16:13.910
a cheer for my
employees, I'd have

00:16:13.910 --> 00:16:15.540
no problem getting
people in the room.

00:16:15.540 --> 00:16:20.050
If I had posters of Walt
Disney holding all of his Oscar

00:16:20.050 --> 00:16:21.810
awards, I'd have no problem.

00:16:21.810 --> 00:16:25.560
In fact, the Oscar the Walt won
for "Snow White and the Seven

00:16:25.560 --> 00:16:26.980
Dwarfs" is really cool.

00:16:26.980 --> 00:16:28.710
Has anybody ever seen it?

00:16:28.710 --> 00:16:31.760
It's-- of course the
AV guy's seen it--

00:16:31.760 --> 00:16:34.030
the other old guy in
the room has seen it--

00:16:34.030 --> 00:16:38.010
it's a single Oscar with seven
baby Oscars lined up next

00:16:38.010 --> 00:16:40.540
to it, representing the seven
dwarfs-- posters of that,

00:16:40.540 --> 00:16:43.417
pictures of that,
all over the company.

00:16:43.417 --> 00:16:45.750
So their point-- non-Disney
people will say, well, yeah,

00:16:45.750 --> 00:16:50.290
if I had those fanciful names
and the soundtrack of "Lion

00:16:50.290 --> 00:16:52.580
King" and "Hakuna Matata"
playing in the background

00:16:52.580 --> 00:16:55.019
when I go in to
orientation, of course

00:16:55.019 --> 00:16:56.060
I'm going to be thrilled.

00:16:56.060 --> 00:16:59.480
And I say, yes, but what if
that message that you learned in

00:16:59.480 --> 00:17:02.430
that training program is not
alive and well on the front

00:17:02.430 --> 00:17:02.960
lines?

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:05.240
And that new hire, or
that senior executive,

00:17:05.240 --> 00:17:07.750
goes into the park, or goes
back to his or her job,

00:17:07.750 --> 00:17:09.250
and somebody else
says, I don't care

00:17:09.250 --> 00:17:12.190
what they say in that
brainwashing factory called

00:17:12.190 --> 00:17:13.339
Disney University.

00:17:13.339 --> 00:17:16.270
The real message is right
here, so forget all that crap.

00:17:17.176 --> 00:17:18.800
That would be a
complete waste of time.

00:17:18.800 --> 00:17:20.710
And all too often, I
go into organizations,

00:17:20.710 --> 00:17:23.349
and I actually recommend they
get rid of their training

00:17:23.349 --> 00:17:26.230
department, or at least
their training curriculum,

00:17:26.230 --> 00:17:28.790
because it's not in
tune with real life.

00:17:30.200 --> 00:17:31.740
And I'm a firm
believer in training.

00:17:31.740 --> 00:17:33.031
Everybody should have training.

00:17:33.031 --> 00:17:35.120
But it doesn't always
have to be in a classroom.

00:17:35.120 --> 00:17:36.140
It could be one-on-one.

00:17:36.140 --> 00:17:37.056
It could be mentoring.

00:17:37.056 --> 00:17:39.470
It could be in five-minute
bursts throughout the day

00:17:39.470 --> 00:17:40.935
or throughout the week.

00:17:40.935 --> 00:17:43.060
But this is what-- again
getting back to these four

00:17:43.060 --> 00:17:45.910
circumstances that Van
France talked about,

00:17:45.910 --> 00:17:48.020
and I write about
extensively in "Disney U,"

00:17:48.020 --> 00:17:50.730
because "Disney U," the
book, is about values that

00:17:50.730 --> 00:17:53.890
are timeless and applicable
in the organization.

00:17:53.890 --> 00:17:55.070
And I work with hospitals.

00:17:55.070 --> 00:17:57.520
I work with mom and pop
stores, and everything

00:17:57.520 --> 00:18:01.040
in between-- so Van
said this new baby

00:18:01.040 --> 00:18:04.620
in the corporate family
would not have survived,

00:18:04.620 --> 00:18:07.690
were it not for four
circumstances-- essentially

00:18:07.690 --> 00:18:10.490
four values, and these
values represent, I think,

00:18:10.490 --> 00:18:12.220
the essence of the
Disney organization,

00:18:12.220 --> 00:18:14.110
and I think of all the
companies that I've

00:18:14.110 --> 00:18:16.550
worked with over the years,
you can relate to this

00:18:16.550 --> 00:18:18.520
more so than anybody.

00:18:18.520 --> 00:18:20.670
So the first one is that
Disney as an organization

00:18:20.670 --> 00:18:21.253
of innovation.

00:18:23.230 --> 00:18:24.390
You know about innovation.

00:18:24.390 --> 00:18:25.848
There's nothing to
talk about here,

00:18:25.848 --> 00:18:27.290
but what I want
you think about is

00:18:27.290 --> 00:18:30.640
with your own approach in
sales or services, how much

00:18:30.640 --> 00:18:32.390
do you innovate?

00:18:32.390 --> 00:18:34.320
Yes, the company
is known for this.

00:18:35.530 --> 00:18:37.870
You've got Google X.
You've got innovation time.

00:18:37.870 --> 00:18:39.870
You've got all kinds of
things, but how much are

00:18:39.870 --> 00:18:42.330
you personally challenging
yourself every day

00:18:42.330 --> 00:18:44.010
to innovate and take
calculated risk?

00:18:45.980 --> 00:18:49.260
It's about support--
leadership support--

00:18:49.260 --> 00:18:51.510
the example I just gave you
of Dick Cook, the chairman

00:18:51.510 --> 00:18:54.040
of Disney Studios,
coming in and leading

00:18:54.040 --> 00:18:56.460
a 30-minute discussion
about creativity,

00:18:56.460 --> 00:18:58.930
or the chairman of
Disney Imagineering,

00:18:58.930 --> 00:19:03.500
a guy named Marty Sklar, who
would also work with executives

00:19:03.500 --> 00:19:05.760
and front-line
employees to develop

00:19:05.760 --> 00:19:07.970
creative approaches
to solving problems.

00:19:07.970 --> 00:19:10.400
He had something that he
called "the white sheet

00:19:10.400 --> 00:19:12.336
of paper approach."

00:19:12.336 --> 00:19:13.960
He writes about it
in one of his books.

00:19:13.960 --> 00:19:16.370
And my wife and I were
recently with them,

00:19:16.370 --> 00:19:18.800
spending a whole weekend with
him going over some things,

00:19:18.800 --> 00:19:20.550
and we're going to see
him tomorrow night.

00:19:20.550 --> 00:19:26.530
He said, my staff of Imagineers,
of animators, of creative types

00:19:26.530 --> 00:19:27.465
had massive stress.

00:19:28.630 --> 00:19:30.670
There's 11 Disney theme
parks around the world--

00:19:30.670 --> 00:19:33.310
soon to be 12, with
Shanghai opening next year.

00:19:33.310 --> 00:19:35.500
And he said, the
pressure to outdo

00:19:35.500 --> 00:19:38.590
what you just did last
year in that theme park,

00:19:38.590 --> 00:19:40.570
or on that ride, or in
that movie is massive.

00:19:41.630 --> 00:19:44.290
And so the metaphor that he
used was this piece of paper.

00:19:44.290 --> 00:19:46.780
He said, it's like staring
at a blank piece of paper--

00:19:46.780 --> 00:19:49.030
even if it's a computer
screen, it doesn't matter--

00:19:49.030 --> 00:19:51.560
but that blank piece of
paper scared the heck out

00:19:51.560 --> 00:19:53.380
of a lot of my Imagineers.

00:19:53.380 --> 00:19:56.550
And so I said-- this is Marty
now-- and so I said to them,

00:19:56.550 --> 00:19:59.790
you can look at that blank sheet
of paper in one of two ways.

00:19:59.790 --> 00:20:02.470
You can look at it and say, oh
my gosh, I'm so intimidated,

00:20:02.470 --> 00:20:05.740
because I have to put the
first words on that paper.

00:20:05.740 --> 00:20:07.810
Or you can look at it
and say, oh my gosh,

00:20:07.810 --> 00:20:08.957
isn't this exciting?

00:20:08.957 --> 00:20:10.540
I'm the one who gets
to be the one who

00:20:10.540 --> 00:20:12.630
writes the first
words on this paper.

00:20:13.970 --> 00:20:16.190
So that's innovation.

00:20:16.190 --> 00:20:19.020
That's support from a
guy named Marty Sklar,

00:20:19.020 --> 00:20:22.620
who himself was a writer,
who himself pitched directly

00:20:22.620 --> 00:20:26.680
to Walt Disney the idea for the
$0.10 Disneyland newspaper that

00:20:26.680 --> 00:20:29.270
was sold for years on
Main Street of Disneyland.

00:20:29.270 --> 00:20:31.050
And he pitched that
idea to Walt Disney

00:20:31.050 --> 00:20:32.730
when he was a junior at UCLA.

00:20:35.260 --> 00:20:38.060
So it can happen at any level.

00:20:38.060 --> 00:20:42.770
Thankfully your corporation
encourages innovation,

00:20:42.770 --> 00:20:44.780
and you have tremendous support.

00:20:46.900 --> 00:20:49.990
It's about education and
the value of education.

00:20:49.990 --> 00:20:54.750
Another, I think,
eerily similar value,

00:20:54.750 --> 00:20:57.470
and something that's happening
right here in this room today,

00:20:57.470 --> 00:20:59.511
is something that happened
at the Disney Studios.

00:21:00.450 --> 00:21:03.680
In the mid-1930s,
Walt Disney wanted

00:21:03.680 --> 00:21:06.750
to send his animators
to art school

00:21:06.750 --> 00:21:10.150
to help them be more
creative, and he

00:21:10.150 --> 00:21:11.860
found that the art
schools of the day

00:21:11.860 --> 00:21:15.730
were very limited in their
scope of creativity, actually.

00:21:15.730 --> 00:21:19.220
They actually forced people
into certain boxes and drawing

00:21:19.220 --> 00:21:22.180
styles that Walt didn't
support, but again,

00:21:22.180 --> 00:21:26.400
in his inimitable style of
"no, because as opposed to yes,

00:21:26.400 --> 00:21:29.730
if"-- let's forget about sending
our people to art school.

00:21:29.730 --> 00:21:33.300
Let's invite thought
leaders into Disney Studios.

00:21:33.300 --> 00:21:34.840
And this is in the 1930s.

00:21:34.840 --> 00:21:37.390
He actually invited
Frank Lloyd Wright

00:21:37.390 --> 00:21:39.190
to come in and talk
to the animators

00:21:39.190 --> 00:21:41.000
about how to draw
a better Bambi.

00:21:42.590 --> 00:21:43.840
What is the connection there?

00:21:43.840 --> 00:21:47.510
What they wound up doing,
was they brought a live deer

00:21:47.510 --> 00:21:50.210
into the sound stage,
and they put it

00:21:50.210 --> 00:21:52.340
on a pile of alfalfa hay.

00:21:52.340 --> 00:21:54.670
Now the deer is
munching on alfalfa hay.

00:21:54.670 --> 00:21:57.590
And then around the deer
sit a bunch of animators,

00:21:57.590 --> 00:22:01.660
ostensibly viewing a deer
in its natural resource,

00:22:01.660 --> 00:22:03.530
moving and eating.

00:22:03.530 --> 00:22:07.190
In the day that was
mind-alteringly creative,

00:22:07.190 --> 00:22:09.130
because up until that
point animators had

00:22:09.130 --> 00:22:11.760
to look at real fuzzy
black and white films,

00:22:11.760 --> 00:22:13.470
or they had to look
at photographs.

00:22:13.470 --> 00:22:15.530
They didn't actually
get to see the muscle

00:22:15.530 --> 00:22:17.530
twitch of the animal,
or how the jaw moved

00:22:17.530 --> 00:22:19.500
when it ate the alfalfa.

00:22:19.500 --> 00:22:21.920
And after listening to Frank
Lloyd Wright come in and give

00:22:21.920 --> 00:22:23.870
them ideas about
what he went through

00:22:23.870 --> 00:22:26.110
to create a new
building, they did that.

00:22:28.080 --> 00:22:30.250
