00:33:20.010 --> 00:33:20.926
Get rid of the cramps.

00:33:22.630 --> 00:33:25.360
Now analyze your
handwriting two ways.

00:33:25.360 --> 00:33:28.020
One, do a productivity
assessment-- how many times

00:33:28.020 --> 00:33:29.622
did you actually sign your name?

00:33:29.622 --> 00:33:30.580
Write that number down.

00:33:30.580 --> 00:33:31.490
Don't look at your neighbor.

00:33:31.490 --> 00:33:33.120
It doesn't matter
if you did more.

00:33:33.120 --> 00:33:35.280
You are such a type
a competitive group.

00:33:35.280 --> 00:33:36.204
Just relax .

00:33:36.204 --> 00:33:38.370
Their name might have more
letters in it than yours.

00:33:38.370 --> 00:33:40.210
So do a productivity
assessment--

00:33:40.210 --> 00:33:42.150
how many times did
you sign your name?

00:33:42.150 --> 00:33:44.680
Then I want to do a
quality assessment,

00:33:44.680 --> 00:33:46.430
using a 1 through 10 scale.

00:33:46.430 --> 00:33:49.160
10 is perfect-- oh
my gosh, that's mine.

00:33:49.160 --> 00:33:51.960
1 is who wrote this
chicken scratch?

00:33:51.960 --> 00:33:52.714
10 is great.

00:33:52.714 --> 00:33:53.380
One is terrible.

00:33:53.380 --> 00:33:55.440
Or something in
between for a quality

00:33:55.440 --> 00:33:56.610
score-- purely subjective.

00:33:57.840 --> 00:33:58.590
You all have that?

00:33:58.590 --> 00:33:58.900
Look at me.

00:33:58.900 --> 00:33:59.608
Give me feedback.

00:33:59.608 --> 00:34:01.050
This is yes.

00:34:01.050 --> 00:34:05.050
This is no, and this is
what is this guy doing?

00:34:05.050 --> 00:34:08.424
Now, with pen in dominant
hand, hold that in the air,

00:34:08.424 --> 00:34:10.590
or if you did air writing,
just hold your blank hand

00:34:10.590 --> 00:34:11.230
in the air.

00:34:11.230 --> 00:34:12.889
Keep that hand in the air.

00:34:12.889 --> 00:34:14.600
Raise your non-dominant hand.

00:34:14.600 --> 00:34:15.730
Both hands are in the air.

00:34:15.730 --> 00:34:18.699
Transfer the pen to
the non-dominant hand.

00:34:18.699 --> 00:34:19.780
Hands down.

00:34:19.780 --> 00:34:25.410
Five, four, three, two, one,
proceed-- same exercise,

00:34:25.410 --> 00:34:26.659
30 seconds with your off-hand.

00:34:28.460 --> 00:34:30.855
No laughing-- this is a
very important exercise.

00:34:36.630 --> 00:34:37.820
Stop writing.

00:34:37.820 --> 00:34:38.550
Do me a favor.

00:34:38.550 --> 00:34:40.591
Look at your neighbor's
and laugh uncontrollably.

00:34:48.310 --> 00:34:49.889
Do a productivity assessment.

00:34:49.889 --> 00:34:51.530
How many times did
you sign your name

00:34:51.530 --> 00:34:53.070
with your non-dominant hand?

00:34:53.070 --> 00:34:54.179
Write that number down.

00:34:55.340 --> 00:34:58.107
Next is that quality
score, and this

00:34:58.107 --> 00:34:59.940
is how you're going to
get it-- this 1 to 10

00:34:59.940 --> 00:35:01.890
scale-- look at
your dominant hand

00:35:01.890 --> 00:35:03.740
as the benchmark of excellence.

00:35:03.740 --> 00:35:05.230
That's the perfect model.

00:35:05.230 --> 00:35:08.860
Compare and contrast-- if your
non-dominant hand looks exactly

00:35:08.860 --> 00:35:11.600
like that, give yourself
a 10 for quality.

00:35:11.600 --> 00:35:13.960
Otherwise, drop it down the
scale accordingly-- five,

00:35:13.960 --> 00:35:15.930
three, one, zero,
minus 1 million--

00:35:15.930 --> 00:35:17.660
whatever you think you deserve.

00:35:17.660 --> 00:35:18.920
Take a couple seconds.

00:35:18.920 --> 00:35:20.490
Get that down.

00:35:20.490 --> 00:35:23.052
Three questions-- please,
raise your hands in response.

00:35:23.052 --> 00:35:24.760
Everybody, I want you
to respond to this.

00:35:24.760 --> 00:35:27.030
How many saw a drop-off
in your productivity

00:35:27.030 --> 00:35:28.112
the second time around?

00:35:28.112 --> 00:35:28.820
Raise your hands.

00:35:28.820 --> 00:35:30.760
Look around the room--
beautiful-- hands down.

00:35:30.760 --> 00:35:32.900
How many saw a
drop-off in quality

00:35:32.900 --> 00:35:35.160
the second go around--
beautiful, hands down.

00:35:35.160 --> 00:35:38.590
Last question, how many felt
uncomfortable or downright

00:35:38.590 --> 00:35:41.280
foolish the second go
around-- beautiful.

00:35:42.290 --> 00:35:44.290
That's the answer
to your question.

00:35:44.290 --> 00:35:46.984
We get stuck in ruts because
we don't want to look stupid.

00:35:46.984 --> 00:35:47.900
We don't want to fail.

00:35:48.910 --> 00:35:52.250
Metaphorically, as
a coach of others--

00:35:52.250 --> 00:35:55.800
even when working with clientele
in sales and services--

00:35:55.800 --> 00:36:00.040
I, as a change-agent,
need to recognize the pain

00:36:00.040 --> 00:36:01.740
I'm putting through
that changee.

00:36:03.410 --> 00:36:06.970
Even myself-- I am not
comfortable looking foolish.

00:36:06.970 --> 00:36:08.810
I don't know how to
manage people that way.

00:36:08.810 --> 00:36:10.960
But I'm not going to let
on that I don't know.

00:36:10.960 --> 00:36:16.100
We all have egos-- individually,
as well as organizationally.

00:36:16.100 --> 00:36:17.660
And metaphorically,
the challenge

00:36:17.660 --> 00:36:20.960
is are you willing and able
to move the pen from one hand

00:36:20.960 --> 00:36:21.610
to the other?

00:36:21.610 --> 00:36:24.290
It doesn't mean that you're
giving up that dominant hand

00:36:24.290 --> 00:36:25.270
and skill set.

00:36:25.270 --> 00:36:26.829
It means that
you're adding to it.

00:36:26.829 --> 00:36:28.620
And the reason I feel
strongly about this--

00:36:28.620 --> 00:36:30.820
and I'm going to talk about
it as we go along here--

00:36:30.820 --> 00:36:35.310
is that we at Disney became
so confident and competent

00:36:35.310 --> 00:36:38.840
with our dominant hand,
that we forgot to change.

00:36:40.510 --> 00:36:42.840
You think left and
right, dominant hand

00:36:42.840 --> 00:36:45.750
or non-dominant hand, now
let's change it to people.

00:36:45.750 --> 00:36:50.880
Dreamers and doers represent
the far ends of that continuum.

00:36:50.880 --> 00:36:53.345
Continuum is what we in
the OD business call it.

00:36:53.345 --> 00:36:56.130
It's just a, line for crying
out loud, but it's a line,

00:36:56.130 --> 00:36:58.220
and on the far end what
we're showing up on

00:36:58.220 --> 00:37:01.116
the screen now is Walt
was on the dreamer

00:37:01.116 --> 00:37:01.990
end of the continuum.

00:37:03.040 --> 00:37:03.760
What if?

00:37:03.760 --> 00:37:05.140
What are we going to do?

00:37:05.140 --> 00:37:07.360
It's Google X, right?

00:37:07.360 --> 00:37:09.924
And you have to make
things go to market.

00:37:09.924 --> 00:37:10.840
You got to make money.

00:37:10.840 --> 00:37:12.290
You got to make
it happen somehow.

00:37:12.290 --> 00:37:14.030
You got to produce this thing.

00:37:14.030 --> 00:37:15.680
So you have to have doers.

00:37:15.680 --> 00:37:19.370
Walt Disney and his brother
Roy were the classic balance

00:37:19.370 --> 00:37:20.490
of dreamer, doer.

00:37:20.490 --> 00:37:22.660
You don't agree with
everything they say.

00:37:22.660 --> 00:37:25.410
But at least you have
that contrarian thinker.

00:37:26.690 --> 00:37:29.600
Teams that have both
are amazingly strong.

00:37:29.600 --> 00:37:32.980
But unfortunately, only about
7% of companies around the world

00:37:32.980 --> 00:37:35.360
have a succession plan.

00:37:35.360 --> 00:37:38.050
And we at Disney
fell into that trap.

00:37:38.050 --> 00:37:40.610
With both dreamers and
doers on your team--

00:37:40.610 --> 00:37:42.610
regardless of how old
they are or how many years

00:37:42.610 --> 00:37:44.680
of experience--
you will continue

00:37:44.680 --> 00:37:45.780
to dominate your market.

00:37:45.780 --> 00:37:49.010
You will continue to have
a culture that evolves,

00:37:49.010 --> 00:37:50.280
challenges itself.

00:37:50.280 --> 00:37:52.829
But with one, you're done.

00:37:52.829 --> 00:37:54.620
So I want to share with
you a quote, again,

00:37:54.620 --> 00:37:56.590
from this gentleman
Marty Sklar that

00:37:56.590 --> 00:38:01.370
spent 53 years in his career
with the Disney organization,

00:38:01.370 --> 00:38:04.940
and he talked about the
mindset that Walt Disney had.

00:38:04.940 --> 00:38:08.060
Walt Disney in, Marty's words,
as I'm showing on the screen,

00:38:08.060 --> 00:38:10.940
"always had one foot in the past
and one foot in the future."

00:38:10.940 --> 00:38:14.650
He recognized the importance
of the legacy of the company.

00:38:14.650 --> 00:38:16.850
And legacy is a relative
term-- for some companies

00:38:16.850 --> 00:38:19.930
it's 16 years, for some
companies it's decades,

00:38:19.930 --> 00:38:21.990
for some it's just
a couple of years.

00:38:21.990 --> 00:38:24.540
In Silicon Valley, a long legacy
is a day, and you're done.

00:38:24.540 --> 00:38:25.180
It's OK.

00:38:25.180 --> 00:38:28.202
But he, meaning Walt,
didn't hang out in the past.

00:38:28.202 --> 00:38:29.910
He knew that it was
important to leverage

00:38:29.910 --> 00:38:32.170
that to go to the future
and upset the apple

00:38:32.170 --> 00:38:34.570
cart, constantly moving
the pen, metaphorically,

00:38:34.570 --> 00:38:35.840
left to right, right to left.

00:38:35.840 --> 00:38:38.260
But when Walt passed
away, the tendency

00:38:38.260 --> 00:38:42.060
was for the doer
mindset to take over--

00:38:42.060 --> 00:38:45.100
not upset the apple cart,
not make any mistakes,

00:38:45.100 --> 00:38:46.940
keep the pen in
that dominant hand.

00:38:48.500 --> 00:38:51.839
Another way to look at it is
something called the "S curve."

00:38:51.839 --> 00:38:53.380
Has anybody ever
studied the S curve?

00:38:54.874 --> 00:38:56.040
You might want to Google it.

00:38:56.040 --> 00:38:56.800
Check it out.

00:38:56.800 --> 00:38:59.240
But it's also known
as the sigmoid curve.

00:38:59.240 --> 00:39:01.010
Now if you've had
a sigmoidoscopy,

00:39:01.010 --> 00:39:02.640
you don't want to
think about that.

00:39:02.640 --> 00:39:04.310
So we'll just call the S curve.

00:39:04.310 --> 00:39:07.660
But it's basically the letter
"S" kind of lying on its side.

00:39:07.660 --> 00:39:11.010
And it basically represents
the beginning, middle, and end.

00:39:11.010 --> 00:39:14.410
It's a life cycle of
anything-- an idea, a product,

00:39:14.410 --> 00:39:17.670
a color scheme, hairstyles,
whatever the case might be.

00:39:17.670 --> 00:39:20.490
And if you have dreamers
and doers on a team,

00:39:20.490 --> 00:39:23.530
then you're guaranteed of
having multiple S curves going

00:39:23.530 --> 00:39:27.420
in the air, and many things
being juggled at the same time.

00:39:27.420 --> 00:39:29.480
If you only have
one or the other,

00:39:29.480 --> 00:39:32.150
generally, the marketplace
has changed around you,

00:39:32.150 --> 00:39:36.100
and you didn't realize it,
or you're producing products

00:39:36.100 --> 00:39:37.790
that nobody cares about anymore.

00:39:37.790 --> 00:39:40.360
And most organizations
don't change

00:39:40.360 --> 00:39:43.750
until they get to point
z, and that's too late.

00:39:43.750 --> 00:39:46.640
And this is exactly what
happened to us at Disney.

00:39:46.640 --> 00:39:48.290
When Walt Disney
passed away, and we

00:39:48.290 --> 00:39:50.900
lost that creative
force, and the person who

00:39:50.900 --> 00:39:53.370
was willing and able to
upset the apple cart,

00:39:53.370 --> 00:39:55.930
and everybody was busy
circling wagons to make sure

00:39:55.930 --> 00:39:58.110
that nothing changed,
we got in trouble.

00:39:59.530 --> 00:40:01.620
So I want to think about--
this quote right now,

00:40:01.620 --> 00:40:04.267
I think, is particularly
poignant for Google.

00:40:04.267 --> 00:40:06.100
You're at your 10th
anniversary of your IPO.

00:40:07.170 --> 00:40:09.650
This quote is from Walt
Disney at the 10th anniversary

00:40:09.650 --> 00:40:10.840
of Disneyland.

00:40:10.840 --> 00:40:12.140
Disneyland opened in '55.

00:40:12.140 --> 00:40:14.860
This is from a meeting that
he had with his executive team

00:40:14.860 --> 00:40:18.340
and operations team in 1965.

00:40:18.340 --> 00:40:20.100
And of many things
that he said, he said,

00:40:20.100 --> 00:40:22.770
we've had 10 years of
knock-the-ball-out-of-the-park

00:40:22.770 --> 00:40:23.330
success.

00:40:23.330 --> 00:40:24.990
And he talked about
all the accolades

00:40:24.990 --> 00:40:28.170
from around the world of
starting this theme park called

00:40:28.170 --> 00:40:30.404
Disneyland that no one had
ever dreamed of before.

00:40:30.404 --> 00:40:32.570
In the past, it was you
should go to the state fair.

00:40:32.570 --> 00:40:33.850
Or you go to a county fair.

00:40:33.850 --> 00:40:36.170
And you know what kind
of quality you get there.

00:40:37.156 --> 00:40:38.530
And Walt said,
but you know what?

00:40:38.530 --> 00:40:42.520
I look at these first
10 years as nothing more

00:40:42.520 --> 00:40:47.060
than a dress rehearsal-- nothing
more than a dress rehearsal.

00:40:47.060 --> 00:40:48.710
And if any of you
on this team think

00:40:48.710 --> 00:40:52.090
you can rest on your laurels,
then there's the door.

00:40:52.090 --> 00:40:55.570
That's what keeps an
organization young and dynamic,

00:40:55.570 --> 00:40:58.040
is you've always got
that pressure to perform.

00:40:58.040 --> 00:41:00.580
And you can look at
that as massive stress.

00:41:00.580 --> 00:41:03.320
Or you could look at as
tremendous opportunity.

00:41:03.320 --> 00:41:08.030
And when Walt passed away, some
of that went away with him.

00:41:11.570 --> 00:41:14.080
Another thing that
went away with him--

00:41:14.080 --> 00:41:17.300
and this is another part about
keeping an organizational

00:41:17.300 --> 00:41:20.720
culture alive and well-- is
a term that we use a Disney

00:41:20.720 --> 00:41:23.490
called "plussing the
show"-- improving the show.

00:41:23.490 --> 00:41:25.000
I'll give you one
specific example

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:26.380
that I write about
in "Disney U."

00:41:26.380 --> 00:41:28.820
One of the directors of
the Disney University

00:41:28.820 --> 00:41:31.270
told me a story about when
he was an 18-year-old ride

00:41:31.270 --> 00:41:32.630
operator at Disneyland.

00:41:32.630 --> 00:41:34.820
And Walt Disney came into
the park all the time.

00:41:34.820 --> 00:41:36.680
Walt was known to walk the park.

00:41:36.680 --> 00:41:40.970
He was always in direct contact
with guests and cast members.

00:41:40.970 --> 00:41:43.240
Walt Disney rode
on jungle cruise?

00:41:43.240 --> 00:41:45.100
Anybody ever ridden on
Jungle Cruise before?

00:41:45.100 --> 00:41:46.450
Fantastic ride.

00:41:46.450 --> 00:41:49.400
And Walt gone off of the boat--
there are seven boats on jungle

00:41:49.400 --> 00:41:52.040
cruise-- he got off of the boat
and pulled all the skippers off

00:41:52.040 --> 00:41:53.540
to the side on the
dock to give them

00:41:53.540 --> 00:41:55.100
some fairly critical feedback.

00:41:56.180 --> 00:41:57.770
He said, we've got
to plus the show.

00:41:57.770 --> 00:41:59.999
If we don't plus the
show we'll lose guests,

00:41:59.999 --> 00:42:01.790
and it will take us
years to get them back.

00:42:01.790 --> 00:42:04.440
And this is the specific
example he gave-- he said,

00:42:04.440 --> 00:42:05.860
we've invested
millions of dollars

00:42:05.860 --> 00:42:08.010
in this attraction--
in the soundtrack,

00:42:08.010 --> 00:42:10.660
in the audio
animatronic figures.

00:42:10.660 --> 00:42:14.000
And he said, and each of
you skippers undermine that.

00:42:15.180 --> 00:42:17.470
And this guy said, well,
what do we do, Walt?

00:42:17.470 --> 00:42:18.930
He said, well, you
think about it.

00:42:18.930 --> 00:42:20.702
In this seven-minute
ride, when we

00:42:20.702 --> 00:42:22.160
get to about the
middle of the ride

00:42:22.160 --> 00:42:25.570
where the jungle is
encroaching on us,

00:42:25.570 --> 00:42:28.070
and the boats are getting into
that real, dark scary part

00:42:28.070 --> 00:42:30.880
of the jungle, and the river
is really dark, dark green,

00:42:30.880 --> 00:42:32.430
what happens at
that moment, when

00:42:32.430 --> 00:42:34.394
everybody's on pins and needles?

00:42:34.394 --> 00:42:37.060
And the skippers all said, well,
that's when the hippos jump out

00:42:37.060 --> 00:42:39.150
of the water-- the hippopotamus.

00:42:39.150 --> 00:42:40.310
And Walt said, exactly.

00:42:40.310 --> 00:42:41.990
And what do those hippos do?

00:42:41.990 --> 00:42:42.940
Well, they roar.

00:42:42.940 --> 00:42:43.800
And they scream.

00:42:43.800 --> 00:42:45.580
And they spit water.

00:42:45.580 --> 00:42:48.287
He said, yes, and they
spit water on the guests,

00:42:48.287 --> 00:42:49.120
and they make noise.

00:42:49.120 --> 00:42:51.170
And what are the
guests are doing?

00:42:51.170 --> 00:42:53.360
Well, they're screaming
with delight and fright.

00:42:53.360 --> 00:42:55.540
Exactly, said Walt.

00:42:55.540 --> 00:42:57.790
What were each of
you skippers doing?

00:42:57.790 --> 00:42:59.730
And then Walt
demonstrated to them--

00:42:59.730 --> 00:43:06.160
this is driving a boat-- [YAWNS]
another day, another hippo.

00:43:07.600 --> 00:43:08.510
You killed the show.

00:43:10.770 --> 00:43:12.985
You've got a week to
practice looking surprised.

00:43:14.662 --> 00:43:16.370
And this guy that I
interviewed, he said,

00:43:16.370 --> 00:43:18.010
and you can only
imagine how many hours

00:43:18.010 --> 00:43:20.940
we spent the next week
practicing looking surprised,

00:43:20.940 --> 00:43:23.120
knowing full well that
Walt was going to be back.

00:43:23.120 --> 00:43:26.440
And he said, but what was
interesting about this process,

00:43:26.440 --> 00:43:29.240
was that at first it was just
pretending to look surprised.

00:43:29.240 --> 00:43:31.340
But then, as we did
it more and more,

00:43:31.340 --> 00:43:35.480
we realized this is a brand
new boatload of guests,

00:43:35.480 --> 00:43:37.470
and for then this is a
brand new experience.

00:43:37.470 --> 00:43:39.555
And we started to
feel their excitement.

00:43:40.620 --> 00:43:41.940
So here is Walt Disney, again.

00:43:41.940 --> 00:43:44.730
This brilliant man who
said, millions of dollars

00:43:44.730 --> 00:43:47.920
invested in the hardware,
but you're the software.

00:43:47.920 --> 00:43:49.910
How much does a smile cost?

00:43:49.910 --> 00:43:51.805
That keeps an
organization fresh,

00:43:51.805 --> 00:43:53.770
and it's an example
of plussing the show.

00:43:56.020 --> 00:43:58.215
It means that we
all make mistakes.

00:43:58.215 --> 00:44:00.590
This artwork is from another
book that I wrote years ago.

00:44:00.590 --> 00:44:02.423
It's from a proverb
that I learned in Japan.

00:44:03.340 --> 00:44:06.830
And the proverb is this--
even monkeys fall from trees.

00:44:06.830 --> 00:44:10.320
No matter how good you are, no
matter your name recognition--

00:44:10.320 --> 00:44:12.010
domestically or
internationally--

00:44:12.010 --> 00:44:14.190
you will screw up.

00:44:14.190 --> 00:44:16.750
And all too often, organizations
and individual managers

00:44:16.750 --> 00:44:20.474
blame that metaphorical gust
of wind, or the broken branch,

00:44:20.474 --> 00:44:22.390
for the reason they're
flat on their backside,

00:44:22.390 --> 00:44:25.300
as opposed to looking in
the mirror and assessing

00:44:25.300 --> 00:44:26.790
how they could improve.

00:44:26.790 --> 00:44:30.460
So here is something I'd
like to share with you,

00:44:30.460 --> 00:44:32.680
and then I'm going to start
to bring this to a close.

00:44:32.680 --> 00:44:36.020
This is a picture of that
wonderful, beautiful man,

00:44:36.020 --> 00:44:36.610
Van France.

00:44:37.660 --> 00:44:40.790
This is the guy that created
the Disney University.

00:44:40.790 --> 00:44:42.650
How many of you been
to the Disney Institute

00:44:42.650 --> 00:44:44.080
with the B.A. Program?

00:44:44.080 --> 00:44:44.640
Some of you?

00:44:44.640 --> 00:44:46.990
I heard that quite a few,
actually, at Google do.

00:44:46.990 --> 00:44:49.630
The Disney Institute is
the for-public version

00:44:49.630 --> 00:44:52.910
of the university,
which Van started.

00:44:52.910 --> 00:44:57.780
So this set of words is part
of a memo than Van France sent

00:44:57.780 --> 00:45:00.180
to Walt Disney and something
called the Park Operating

00:45:00.180 --> 00:45:04.420
Committee to challenge
them on being more creative

00:45:04.420 --> 00:45:09.330
in being better leaders,
creating better training,

00:45:09.330 --> 00:45:10.700
keeping the product fresh.

00:45:12.200 --> 00:45:13.820
Look at the word choice in here.

00:45:13.820 --> 00:45:16.430
Has anybody ever used
the word "arthritis

00:45:16.430 --> 00:45:21.030
of the imagination," or
"cirrhosis of the enthusiasm"?

00:45:21.030 --> 00:45:23.370
And this is the
brilliance of Van France--

00:45:23.370 --> 00:45:27.570
just like Walt Disney-- really,
really honest, brutally honest,

00:45:27.570 --> 00:45:29.290
and a great salesperson.

00:45:29.290 --> 00:45:31.850
He knew that if he
didn't package a memo

00:45:31.850 --> 00:45:35.316
in a creative enough way, that
Walt and the team of executives

00:45:35.316 --> 00:45:36.690
wouldn't pay any
attention to it.

00:45:37.830 --> 00:45:39.770
So my question to
you is this, who

00:45:39.770 --> 00:45:44.200
is the Van France on your team,
within sales and services?

00:45:44.200 --> 00:45:45.910
Who is the person
who's not afraid to say

00:45:45.910 --> 00:45:46.900
what he or she sees?

00:45:48.030 --> 00:45:50.260
Now, I understand in any
organization there's always

00:45:50.260 --> 00:45:53.710
going to be politics involved,
but people like Van France

00:45:53.710 --> 00:45:56.340
always find ways to get the
truth to the right people.

00:45:59.520 --> 00:46:01.880
So I'm going to finish up
with another little exercise,

00:46:01.880 --> 00:46:04.190
just to have you get
a little bit of energy

00:46:04.190 --> 00:46:07.120
before you got to go back
out into the Bay area traffic

00:46:07.120 --> 00:46:08.274
and drive home.

00:46:08.274 --> 00:46:09.690
I want you think
about creativity.

00:46:11.830 --> 00:46:14.340
Something as simple as
"how clean is clean?"

00:46:14.340 --> 00:46:16.120
Before we opened
Tokyo Disneyland,

00:46:16.120 --> 00:46:19.832
the team of custodians
that I hired and trained

00:46:19.832 --> 00:46:20.665
made a huge mistake.

00:46:22.430 --> 00:46:26.124
The night before our
first mini-grand opening,

00:46:26.124 --> 00:46:27.790
we had executives
from the United States

00:46:27.790 --> 00:46:29.950
tell them, hey, go out
tonight, and clean the park,

00:46:29.950 --> 00:46:32.460
because Disney is
known for cleanliness.

00:46:32.460 --> 00:46:35.870
And we had spent months training
them on cleaning the park.

00:46:35.870 --> 00:46:37.620
And it was all interpreted
perfectly well.

00:46:37.620 --> 00:46:38.780
And so they said,
yes, we understand.

00:46:38.780 --> 00:46:40.170
We're going to clean the park.

00:46:40.170 --> 00:46:43.640
This is the graveyard crew--
midnight, 3 o'clock, 4 o'clock,

00:46:43.640 --> 00:46:44.884
everything goes fine.

00:46:44.884 --> 00:46:46.550
4 o'clock in morning,
I get a phone call

00:46:46.550 --> 00:46:48.500
from a very upset
American executive.

00:46:48.500 --> 00:46:51.840
What is wrong with those
custodians you hired

00:46:51.840 --> 00:46:52.960
and you trained?

00:46:52.960 --> 00:46:55.260
And I said, nothing-- we
hired the best custodians

00:46:55.260 --> 00:46:56.672
from around the country.

00:46:56.672 --> 00:46:58.130
He said, well, then
answer me this,

00:46:58.130 --> 00:47:00.225
why did they clean
The Haunted Mansion?

00:47:02.540 --> 00:47:04.417
I said, what's the problem?

00:47:04.417 --> 00:47:05.500
It's supposed to be clean.

00:47:05.500 --> 00:47:07.490
He says, no, no,
you don't get it.

00:47:07.490 --> 00:47:09.140
They fixed all the
broken windows.

00:47:10.150 --> 00:47:11.630
They vacuumed up all the dust.

00:47:11.630 --> 00:47:13.370
All the spider webs are gone.

00:47:13.370 --> 00:47:15.270
Literally in about
four hours, they

00:47:15.270 --> 00:47:19.210
had cleaned away a quarter
million dollars of artwork.

00:47:19.210 --> 00:47:21.290
It no longer looked
spooky and scary.

00:47:21.290 --> 00:47:23.450
It looked like an
operating room.

00:47:23.450 --> 00:47:26.150
And the trouble was this-- and
we did a root cause analysis--

00:47:26.150 --> 00:47:30.090
it's because we trained them
in backstage areas that weren't

00:47:30.090 --> 00:47:34.750
aged and grained-- kitchens,
restrooms, break areas that

00:47:34.750 --> 00:47:36.584
had a lot of stainless
steel and white tile.

00:47:36.584 --> 00:47:38.458
And when they would
scrub it until it shined,

00:47:38.458 --> 00:47:39.850
we would say, bravo, good job!

00:47:41.100 --> 00:47:44.280
And they took that same approach
into The Haunted Mansion.

00:47:44.280 --> 00:47:47.320
So again, communication
is not easy.

00:47:47.320 --> 00:47:49.230
And as our teams
get more diverse,

00:47:49.230 --> 00:47:52.650
based on age,
ethnicity, culture,

00:47:52.650 --> 00:47:54.557
it gets even more complicated.

00:47:54.557 --> 00:47:56.390
So I'm going to finish
this with that story.

00:47:56.390 --> 00:47:57.790
It's written about
in "Disney U."

00:47:57.790 --> 00:48:00.110
I want to thank you all
so much for your time.

00:48:00.110 --> 00:48:02.180
I know but you've got
very, very busy schedules.

00:48:02.180 --> 00:48:04.510
Keep up the good work
and keep your culture

00:48:04.510 --> 00:48:06.480
alive and well
and ever-evolving.

00:48:06.480 --> 00:48:08.510
Thank you so much.

